Objective of Assignment 1

The objective of this assignment is to produce a clean, normalized dataset that will be used for the following tasks in this course.

Dataset Overview

-Secretase is a protease known to cleave the CTFs of amyloid-beta precursor protein (APP) at its gamma site. It is also known to cleave other substrates, and has been associated pathways governing cell differentiation. However, we still do not have a full understanding of what -Secretase does to non-proliferating cells (such as neurons).

Dysfunction of lipid metabolism neurons has been linked with Alzheimers Disease. In mouse embryonic fibroblasts (MEFs), -secretase inhibition lowered cellular cholesterol ester levels and reduced endocytosis of the low-density lipoprotein receptor (LDLR). However, No studies were carried out in human neurons, whose cholesterol metabolism is uniquely different from that of glia or peripheral cells.

The authors conducted RNA-seq experiments six biological replicates of induced human neuron cells. There were three treatment protocols: Control, DAPT, and LY411575. Specifically, DAPT and LY411575 treatments pharmaceutically induced chronic inhibition of -secretase. The associated GEO ID for this dataset is GSE206102.

Downloading the Dataset

# get the expression data

tar_sup_filename = supp_files$fname[1]

# untar files
download_dir <- file.path(getwd())
untar(tarfile = file.path(download_dir,dataset_geo_id,tar_sup_filename),
      exdir = file.path(download_dir,dataset_geo_id))

Now that the data has been uncompressed, we can begin reading and combining all the files.

# Function to extract information from the filename
extract_info <- function(file) {
  parts <- strsplit(basename(file), "_")[[1]]
  data_id <- parts[1]
  sample_name <- toString(
    samples_type[, "title"][grep(data_id, rownames(samples_type))]
    )
  sample_name <- gsub(sample_name, pattern = "Replicate", replacement = "rep")
  return(sample_name)
  }

# get all the untarred files
file_list <- list.files(
  path = file.path(download_dir, dataset_geo_id), 
  pattern = "\\.hs.tsv.gz$", 
  full.names = TRUE
)

# load list of dataframes
data_list <- lapply(file_list, function(file) {
  df <- read.table(file, header = TRUE)
  df <- df[c("target_id", "est_counts")]
  
  counts_col <- extract_info(file)
  
  # replace 'est_counts' with a more readable name
  colnames(df)[colnames(df) == "est_counts"] <- counts_col
  return(df)
})

# combine list of dataframes using the appropriate ID
combined_table <- data_list %>% reduce(left_join, by = "target_id")

head(combined_table)

Step 2: Cleaning the Data

This step is necessary as the data table we have compiled contains counts at the transcript level. We must first map this data to the proper HUGO symbols before proceeding to any other steps. We can use biomaRt to accomplish this.

Filtering the Data

Now that we have a table with the appropriate HUGO gene symbol for each transcript, we can begin actually filtering the data.

# remove rows that do not have HUGO symbol
hgnc_combined_table <- hgnc_combined_table[
  !is.na(hgnc_combined_table$external_gene_name), ]

# counts are currently still on the transcript-level
hgnc_combined_table <- subset(hgnc_combined_table, select = -c(target_id))

# we are summing the transcript count values when they share the same gene ID
hgnc_combined_table <- hgnc_combined_table %>%
  group_by(external_gene_name) %>%
  summarise_all(sum)

dim(hgnc_combined_table)
## [1] 30895    19

Now that we have gene-level counts, we can start filtering out the low-count genes

# there are 6 samples for each condition, removing low counts
min_samples <- 6
keep <- rowSums( edgeR::cpm(subset(hgnc_combined_table, 
                                   select = -c(external_gene_name)))
                 > 1 ) >= min_samples
filtered_table <- hgnc_combined_table[keep, ]
dim(filtered_table)

Now that we have cleaned our data, we can now proceed to the normalization step. Before this, we must look at how our data looks pre-normalized.

The overall distributions between the samples look almost identical, with medians and quartiles at the same values. We will nevertheless still apply a normalization to see what it looks like. This is confirmed by the density plot, as shown below:

Questions and Answers

What are the control and test conditions of the dataset?
The RNA-seq experiment was conducted over siz biological replicates of induced neuronal cells. Tehre were three treatments: control (0.6% DMSO), DAPT(40 uM), and LY411575(2.5 uM). The latter two treatments were used to chronically inhibit -secretase.

Why is the dataset of interest to you?
Alzheimers disease (AD); it is the most common cause of dementia but there havent been any successful therapeutic interventions for this issue. More recently, there have been interesting observations regarding the relationship between dysfunction in lipid metabolism and neuroinflammation in AD. This dataset and its associate paper aims to elucidate this relationship by investigating the direct causal relationship between -secretase, cholesterol, and synapses.

Were there expression values that were not unique for specific genes?
This dataset was originally published at the transcript level using ensembl transcript IDs. After mapping these transcripts to their corresponding HUGO symbols, there were many duplicates, as multiple transcripts can be mapped to the same gene. In order fix this issue, I simply summed over the counts of transcripts that mapped to the same gene.

Were there expression values that couldnt be mapped to HUGO symbols?
There were a few transcripts in the original dataset that likely had outdated ensembl IDs, as biomaRt was unable to locate their HUGO symbol. After the conversion step from transcript to gene-level expression, 3300 transcripts were omitted from the dataset.

How many outliers were removed?
I did not remove any sample outliers. As shown by the density and box plots, it seems as though the dataset had already been normalized, as there were no indication of outliers. Hence, no removal of data was performed in this step. The only data that was removed were for low counts; genes were considered expressed when it had >1 count in at least 6 samples.

How did you handle replicates?
The dataset contained six biological replicates, each with three treatments. Thus, the final output data table has 18 columns (six biological replicates, each with three treatments). Note that when removing genes with low sample counts, I removed entire rows to keep the data well-organized.

What is the final coverage of your dataset?
The final dataset coverage is 14380 genes. There are 18 columns (six biological replicates, each with three treatments).
